comment:
instead of a nail gun I'd recommend a battery drill and impact driver with wood screws.
screws tend to be more forgiving in that if you get something wrong it's easier to take them out and put them back in some place else. For a professional carpenter (which I'm not but a relation was) they tend to know they're going to get it right first time so use nails for that reason.
The impact driver makes putting screws in a breeze compared to a drill, but you tend to want to drill a smaller hole sometimes before putting the screw in so that the wood doesn't split. Also you have to be careful to put lots of pressure on when using an impact driver to avoid damaging the head of the screw if it skips around.
